    "Sergei Witte became the first Prime Minister (officially the Chairman of the Council of Ministers) of the Russian Empire on **October 19, 1905**[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergei_Witte), [2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergei_Witte).\n\n### Circumstances of His Appointment\nWitte\u2019s appointment occurred during a period of acute national crisis, defined by the following circumstances:\n\n*   **Political Instability and Unrest:** By 1905, the Russian Empire was engulfed in widespread revolutionary activity, including worker strikes, peasant uprisings, and military mutinies, which threatened the stability of the Romanov throne.\n[3](https://www.britannica.com/summary/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [4](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte)*   **The Russo-Japanese War:** Russia had recently suffered a humiliating defeat in the Russo-Japanese War. [4](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [5](https://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/wittebio.php)Witte had been sent to the United States in the summer of 1905 to negotiate a peace treaty. [4](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [5](https://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/wittebio.php)Despite the difficult position Russia was in, he succeeded in securing unexpectedly favorable terms, which significantly bolstered his political standing upon his return.\n[3](https://www.britannica.com/summary/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [4](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte)*   **The October Manifesto:** Faced with the threat of total revolution, Witte persuaded Tsar Nicholas II that drastic reforms were necessary to preserve the monarchy. [3](https://www.britannica.com/summary/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [5](https://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/wittebio.php)He was the primary architect of the **October Manifesto** (issued on October 17, 1905), which promised civil liberties and the creation of a representative legislative body (the Duma), effectively transitioning Russia into a constitutional monarchy.\n[3](https://www.britannica.com/summary/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [4](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [5](https://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/wittebio.php)*   **The Restructuring of Government:** Following the issuance of the Manifesto, Witte was appointed to lead the government as the first \"Prime Minister\" (Chairman of the Council of Ministers). [1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergei_Witte), [5](https://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/wittebio.php)His primary mandate was to restore order, suppress the ongoing revolutionary forces, and secure foreign loans to stabilize Russia's collapsed finances.\n[3](https://www.britannica.com/summary/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [4](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte)\nAlthough Witte successfully stabilized the regime, his relationship with Tsar Nicholas II remained fraught with tension. [4](https://www.britannica.com/biography/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [5](https://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/wittebio.php)The Tsar, who deeply resented being forced to curtail his autocratic powers, eventually lost confidence in Witte, leading to his dismissal in April 1906.[3](https://www.britannica.com/summary/Sergey-Yulyevich-Graf-Witte), [6](https://brill.com/downloadpdf/display/book/9789004213432/Bej.9781905246038.i-516_006.pdf), [5](https://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/wittebio.php)"
